1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,280
 Bok, ja sam Iva Kraljević i dobrodošli u podcast. Danas imam čast razgovarati sa izuzetnom gošćom, zove se Ramona Treviño,

2
00:00:16,280 --> 00:00:26,060
 if I pronounce it correctly. Yes, that is correct. Good job. Ramona je osoba čija je životna priča snažno odjetknula u ProLife zajednici,

3
00:00:26,060 --> 00:00:35,320
 a danas ćemo čuti i zašto. I kako je od boditeljice klinike Planned Parenthooda, odnosno planiranog roditeljstva,

4
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:43,900
 prešla na stranu borbe za zaštitu života od začeća i što je se između toga izdogađalo u njezinom životu.

5
00:00:51,420 --> 00:01:00,680
 Dej Ramona, it's really an honor and a pleasure having you here. Thank you for being here and thank you for being willing to share your powerful story with our podcast listeners.

6
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:05,560
 Well, it's definitely my honor to be here with you in Croatia. Such a blessing. So thank you.

7
00:01:05,560 --> 00:01:06,680
 Thank you. How do you like Croatia so far?

8
00:01:06,680 --> 00:01:07,680
 I'm loving it. It's beautiful.

9
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:09,680
 I hope we will see you again.

10
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:10,680
 I hope so, yes.

11
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:18,720
 Okay. Let's start, shall we? Maybe from the beginning. How did you end up working for the Planned Parenthood in the first place?

12
00:01:18,720 --> 00:01:23,980
 Yeah. And what made you reconsider your role there?

13
00:01:23,980 --> 00:01:41,720
 Yes. So as you can imagine, that is the most popular question that people have because especially coming from, you know, Planned Parenthood and then now becoming pro-life, the first question is how did you end up at Planned Parenthood, right?

14
00:01:41,720 --> 00:02:01,980
 Right. And I think for most former workers, abortion workers, that is probably one of the most common questions. And I've spent a lot of time, especially since leaving over the years, thinking about that because I don't think it's just a very simple answer.

15
00:02:01,980 --> 00:02:19,140
 I think for many of us, it's more complicated as to how we end up at Planned Parenthood. And I think what I've come to terms with is a very easy answer, which is Satan capitalizes on our trauma and our sin.

16
00:02:19,140 --> 00:02:31,740
 And he looks for an opportunity to take advantage of us when we're vulnerable. And obviously, I played a role in accepting the position for work, you know, working for Planned Parenthood.

17
00:02:31,740 --> 00:02:41,780
 But then when I dive a little deeper into my past, I realized why I was so easily deceived into believing that I was helping women.

18
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:51,780
 And that, I think, came from I was a teen mom. So I became pregnant at 16 years old and had my daughter when I was 17.

19
00:02:51,780 --> 00:03:04,980
 But I was in a very abusive relationship with the father of my daughter for eight years and then was finally found the courage to leave that abusive relationship and face life as a single mother.

20
00:03:04,980 --> 00:03:19,980
 But I never sought healing from that trauma. I never sought any type of psychological help or therapy or or I didn't even go to God to ask for those wounds to be healed.

21
00:03:19,980 --> 00:03:35,180
 And there were a lot of wounds. And so I think, you know, when I think about it, when this opportunity presented itself to work for Planned Parenthood, because abortions didn't happen under my roof, you know, they weren't happening in that center.

22
00:03:35,180 --> 00:03:42,900
 I thought that I was helping the prevent young women from experiencing the things that I had once experienced.

23
00:03:42,900 --> 00:03:47,440
 And I never stopped to consider really what I was involved in.

24
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:52,660
 And so I think that's probably the a little bit more of the longer answer to to it.

25
00:03:52,660 --> 00:04:01,760
 But the simple answer is that's where we often see that Satan has a way of of taking advantage of us in our vulnerability and in our wounds and our hurts.

26
00:04:01,760 --> 00:04:11,320
 And one of the reasons why I always encourage people to seek healing, whether it be professionally from a therapist or from the greatest healer,

27
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:23,220
 which is Jesus Christ, who is capable of healing all wounds, to never leave those things unhealed, because Satan will definitely find a way to capitalize on those wounds.

28
00:04:24,060 --> 00:04:40,720
 And what was the turning point before that? What did you experience at your job that made you, as I said, reconsider or just maybe you felt disappointed or what was it like?

29
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:57,160
 Yeah. So I directed this clinic for three years and I think, you know, for a while after, especially after leaving, I thought, well, I wasn't really involved in really truly evil, you know, because we weren't doing abortions.

30
00:04:57,160 --> 00:05:03,520
 And then I really God really started to reveal to me over time that, yes, I was involved in evil things.

31
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:16,780
 And and so if you talk to someone who directly worked in abortion, who directly saw, you know, the abortions take place, you know, there's there's a different level to to all of this.

32
00:05:16,780 --> 00:05:25,880
 It's another layer, if you will. And for me, I spent those three years justifying, oh, well, I'm not doing abortions here.

33
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:30,540
 It's happening somewhere else. We're just referring women for abortions.

34
00:05:30,540 --> 00:05:37,080
 And and that's what was weighing on my heart that we that I was I was referring women for abortions.

35
00:05:37,080 --> 00:05:39,980
 But I tried the whole time to ignore that.

36
00:05:39,980 --> 00:05:50,660
 But what I couldn't ignore was that I was helping create a market for abortions because really the majority of the women were that were coming into Planned Parenthood weren't women.

37
00:05:50,660 --> 00:06:02,200
 They were children. And so we're talking young girls, you know, 15, 16, 17 years old who are living promiscuously, who are there to get on birth control.

38
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:10,940
 And then ultimately, when those things fail and when that lifestyle catches up to them, if you will, they seek abortions.

39
00:06:10,940 --> 00:06:19,360
 And so you're just creating this revolving door of of of a market that ultimately leads these young girls to abortion.

40
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:29,120
 And that was weighing heavily on my heart because I could see that I wasn't helping prevent these young women from being in situations like I had once been in.

41
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:31,660
 And the only thing I was preventing was children. Right.

42
00:06:31,660 --> 00:06:43,340
 Right. But the but the abuse and the objectification that they were subjecting themselves to was there, you know, and so I was helping perpetuate that in these young girls.

43
00:06:43,340 --> 00:06:49,800
 So you did refer them, you can I say, sent them to the other facility?

44
00:06:49,800 --> 00:06:50,240
 Yes.

45
00:06:50,240 --> 00:07:04,420
 Yeah, because we were all part of the same affiliate. And so of I think there were maybe 26 or 27, I don't remember the exact number clinics in that Planned Parenthood affiliate.

46
00:07:04,420 --> 00:07:14,900
 Two of those is where are where the women went to get their abortions. And so everywhere else were the family planning centers, but still part of the same affiliate.

47
00:07:14,900 --> 00:07:21,000
 And so we were sending everyone into those two, you know, either one of those two abortion facilities.

48
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:33,840
 And so at the end of the day, when I received my paycheck, you know, with Planned Parenthood on it, it was still blood money, you know, because it was all going into one pot, one money pot.

49
00:07:33,840 --> 00:07:39,720
 And I was still getting paid with blood money. And I I tried to ignore that, you know, I didn't want to think about it.

50
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:48,960
 I still wanted to convince myself, you know, that I was doing good things, that I wasn't any different than working for a gynecologist or any other physician.

51
00:07:48,960 --> 00:07:52,900
 Right. But I realized, no, it's not the same thing at all.

52
00:07:52,900 --> 00:08:18,560
 It's an exploitation of women and especially young girls and getting them really to forget about any type of sense of morality when it comes to their sexuality and removing any type of stigma, you know, surrounding promiscuity so that they can live this life of promiscuity that ultimately leads to unplanned pregnancies and crisis pregnancies.

53
00:08:18,560 --> 00:08:27,240
 And really difficult situations to where ultimately they decide to have abortions.

54
00:08:27,240 --> 00:08:44,480
 What was the most common story of those girls? We often hear it's it's probably child conceived in rape or abusive relationship.

55
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:46,160
 Was that the most common story?

56
00:08:46,160 --> 00:08:56,840
 No, no, no. In the United States, incest, rape, those cases are less than one percent of the reasons women have abortions.

57
00:08:56,840 --> 00:09:00,840
 The majority of the reason is just convenience.

58
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:08,840
 It's not a good time. A lot of times these are were young women who were university students or high school students.

59
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:12,520
 So it just wasn't a good thing. Right. And of course, they weren't married.

60
00:09:12,520 --> 00:09:27,520
 They were single. And then also, of course, the fear not wanting their parents to know or fear of, you know, not being able to finish school or not being able to follow their career paths, you know, those type of things.

61
00:09:27,520 --> 00:09:33,120
 So really, it's just abortions out of convenience because it's an inconvenient time to have a baby.

62
00:09:33,120 --> 00:09:41,400
 And then when they enter the Planned Parenthood clinic, what are the options that are presented to them?

63
00:09:41,400 --> 00:09:49,540
 Abortion. That's it. We're not trained on how to counsel or offer life affirming choices whatsoever.

64
00:09:49,540 --> 00:10:05,960
 Yes. On paper, it says that, well, for our particular center, when a young woman comes in for a pregnancy test, there's a question that says, if your pregnancy test is positive, what type of referral would you like?

65
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:18,800
 And then it lists abortion, adoption and prenatal care. But if they choose something other than abortion, the, you know, counseling or the referral just looks like handing over a pamphlet of information.

66
00:10:18,800 --> 00:10:36,340
 That's it. They're not going to receive the type of counseling that you would receive at a pregnancy resource center, what we call pregnancy resource centers back home, in which you're presenting all of the choices that women have and what those consequences of those choices look like.

67
00:10:36,680 --> 00:10:45,240
 Being able to present those to the women so that they can really make an informed decision about what they're going to do.

68
00:10:45,240 --> 00:10:52,000
 Because what happens with Planned Parenthood or any other abortion industry is they're not presenting these young women with all the facts.

69
00:10:52,000 --> 00:11:00,860
 They're not presenting them with, number one, the reality of the biological stage in which they're the gestation right of their baby.

70
00:11:00,860 --> 00:11:14,920
 Like what is going on right now at the gestational age of their pregnancy, they're not presenting them with the facts of what will happen to them emotionally, psychologically, even spiritually after they have an abortion.

71
00:11:14,920 --> 00:11:20,840
 You know, a lot of these women have no idea what to expect after this abortion happens.

72
00:11:20,840 --> 00:11:29,760
 And they paint a very pretty picture for these women so that they can, you know, choose the abortion thinking there's not going to be any type of consequence after.

73
00:11:29,760 --> 00:11:39,060
 Okay. And what happened for you? I mean, what happened then that led to my conversion?

74
00:11:39,060 --> 00:11:40,220
 Led to your conversion, yeah.

75
00:11:40,220 --> 00:11:43,240
 Yes, yes. Well, it was a process, you know.

76
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:47,100
 I think in my eyes, it happened very quickly.

77
00:11:47,100 --> 00:11:52,320
 I think for anyone else looking in, it was probably seemed like it took forever, right?

78
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:55,740
 But for me, it was, it happened, it seemed to have happened very quickly.

79
00:11:55,740 --> 00:12:07,500
 But it was a beautiful process because when I look back, I think of how God loves us and how he, he knows how to reach everyone and meet them exactly where they're at.

80
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:09,720
 And in the way that is necessary, right?

81
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:21,000
 And so for me, it was God really guiding me gently through this process because at the end of the day, it's not an easy, you know, a subject matter, right, that we're dealing with.

82
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:35,540
 The first way in which God reached me was through Catholic radio, which for me is just great to be able to do something like this, a podcast, because we never know how God is going to utilize these things to reach people's hearts.

83
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:38,500
 And so for me, it was through Catholic radio.

84
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:44,600
 I stumbled, if you will, upon Catholic radio accidentally, although I know it was a God incident.

85
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:48,440
 And in the subject they were talking about was abortion.

86
00:12:48,440 --> 00:13:00,100
 They were talking about abortion with women who had had past abortions, who were calling into the program, sharing their very tragic, heart-breaking stories of their past abortions.

87
00:13:00,100 --> 00:13:06,280
 But then they also spoke about contraception and the abortifacient properties of hormonal contraception.

88
00:13:06,280 --> 00:13:20,440
 And that was really the first seed that God planted in my heart that began to really unravel and lead me through this, this complete and total conversion from contraception all the way to abortion.

89
00:13:20,440 --> 00:13:28,280
 And then ultimately, it was through a 40 days for life campaign that the floodgates of grace opened up.

90
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:33,000
 And that's really when things started moving quickly.

91
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,820
 And I realized I needed to quit my job.

92
00:13:36,820 --> 00:13:38,000
 I couldn't work there anymore.

93
00:13:38,500 --> 00:13:41,520
 Can you share with us what was the show about?

94
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:45,800
 What were they saying that's changed your mind?

95
00:13:45,800 --> 00:13:47,180
 On contraception?

96
00:13:47,180 --> 00:13:50,520
 Well, I don't know that it was very dramatic.

97
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:54,520
 I think more than anything, it was just using basic logic and reason.

98
00:13:54,960 --> 00:13:58,020
 I'm a very logical person and I am a deep thinker.

99
00:13:58,020 --> 00:14:00,180
 I think very deeply about different things.

100
00:14:00,180 --> 00:14:03,640
 And I was contracepting for many years at that point.

101
00:14:03,640 --> 00:14:11,200
 And so my attitude toward abortion was that I personally wouldn't have an abortion, right?

102
00:14:11,200 --> 00:14:18,120
 That was my personal belief, even working for Planned Parenthood, was that, oh, well, I wouldn't have an abortion.

103
00:14:18,360 --> 00:14:22,980
 But who am I to tell another woman what she can do, right, with her own body?

104
00:14:22,980 --> 00:14:28,880
 And I had already bought into this lie that, you know, of my body, my choice, right?

105
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:33,560
 That's the big, you know, saying probably all throughout the world, my body, my choice.

106
00:14:33,560 --> 00:14:36,440
 And so I believe that, you know, well, it's not me.

107
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:37,960
 I'm not the one having the abortion.

108
00:14:37,960 --> 00:14:41,700
 So, you know, she can do what she wants to do or, you know, it's not my business.

109
00:14:42,520 --> 00:14:55,540
 But when this presented itself about the contraceptive, hormonal contraceptions working as an abortifacient, I paused and I thought, okay, this is actually something I need to think about.

110
00:14:55,540 --> 00:15:08,800
 Because if I'm contracepting myself, and I've been contracepting for many, many years, on and off for many years, could it be possible that I had had an early, very early termination?

111
00:15:09,380 --> 00:15:23,340
 And actually, there was a moment in where God placed that on my heart and forced me to think back to a time where I think I may have had an early termination while on contraceptive, hormonal contraception.

112
00:15:23,340 --> 00:15:35,160
 And we have to understand first how hormonal contraception works to understand why there is a potential for an early termination.

113
00:15:35,720 --> 00:15:39,180
 And one of the ways is, you know, it prevents ovulation.

114
00:15:39,180 --> 00:15:40,680
 So that's the first thing.

115
00:15:40,680 --> 00:15:48,980
 But when people think, oh, well, you can't have an early termination because you're not, you know, supposed to get pregnant.

116
00:15:48,980 --> 00:15:55,780
 But you can get pregnant while on contraceptives because there can be what we call breakthrough ovulation.

117
00:15:56,360 --> 00:16:05,140
 And I don't know about you or your listeners, but I know many babies that have been born as a result of someone getting pregnant while on contraception.

118
00:16:05,140 --> 00:16:07,500
 And that's because they had breakthrough ovulation.

119
00:16:07,500 --> 00:16:16,340
 And so if this breakthrough ovulation happens, when you're using hormonal contraception, the uterine lining is thinned out.

120
00:16:16,920 --> 00:16:21,900
 And so you have a very thin uterine lining, which makes implantation difficult.

121
00:16:21,900 --> 00:16:36,140
 So if the baby has already been conceived, there's been fertilization, and so you have this new life that could potentially be aborted because it's unable to implant into the uterine wall.

122
00:16:36,140 --> 00:16:43,740
 That doesn't say, that doesn't mean that it's going to happen every time, but there's the potential for it to happen.

123
00:16:44,300 --> 00:16:47,120
 And if it does, women don't know what's happening.

124
00:16:47,120 --> 00:17:00,240
 And so that's when I realized, okay, it challenged me on this mindset of, well, I personally wouldn't do it, but what if I'd been doing it through my own use of contraception?

125
00:17:00,240 --> 00:17:07,300
 And then also, I'm selling contraception to women, and I'm promoting contraception to women.

126
00:17:07,460 --> 00:17:14,480
 So in a sense, I am also involved in direct, I'm involved directly in abortions in a way, right?

127
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:21,220
 And so I think that's where God led me gradually through that process to think about it from that perspective.

128
00:17:21,900 --> 00:17:38,080
 And then, again, like I said, after that, it was a gradual process in which God needed to lead me to a point where I understood that on the issue of abortion, I could not take a position of indifference.

129
00:17:38,080 --> 00:17:41,100
 I had to have, it was black and white.

130
00:17:41,320 --> 00:17:48,920
 And I wanted to believe that I was in this gray, gray area of, oh, well, you know, she can do what she wants, but I wouldn't do it.

131
00:17:48,920 --> 00:18:01,500
 But no, if we know that babies are being taken, their lives are being taken, and we know that abortion is hurting women, and abortion is hurting men, and abortion is hurting families,

132
00:18:01,500 --> 00:18:09,580
 how can we take a position of indifference as our brothers and sisters in the womb are being led to the slaughter?

133
00:18:10,400 --> 00:18:18,320
 And that's where God was leading me to understand that I cannot stand by while innocent human lives are being taken.

134
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:33,260
 You mentioned in one of your podcasts, I think, or somewhere, about the old man who also called in on the show.

135
00:18:33,260 --> 00:18:34,360
 Can you share that, please?

136
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:40,840
 Yeah, so at the end of 40 days after the campaign, I was still at Planned Parenthood.

137
00:18:40,840 --> 00:18:45,440
 Obviously, my heart was already desiring to leave.

138
00:18:45,440 --> 00:18:47,500
 I knew I didn't want to work there anymore.

139
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:57,100
 But because I'm an adult, and I had a family and, you know, bills to pay, I couldn't just quit my job and leave without something else, right?

140
00:18:57,840 --> 00:19:01,640
 And so we've all been in that position where, you know, we have to be responsible.

141
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:07,140
 And so I was really struggling with how do I just quit without another job?

142
00:19:07,140 --> 00:19:08,460
 I have to have another job.

143
00:19:08,460 --> 00:19:11,880
 So I was waiting, you know, to find something else.

144
00:19:12,580 --> 00:19:17,460
 But it was, I had a sense of despair because I thought I can't go on.

145
00:19:17,460 --> 00:19:19,380
 I can't continue here.

146
00:19:19,380 --> 00:19:22,020
 But I also can't quit, you know.

147
00:19:22,020 --> 00:19:27,200
 And so it was actually Easter Tuesday.

148
00:19:27,200 --> 00:19:32,080
 So it was after the campaign ended on Palm Sunday, Easter, we celebrated Easter.

149
00:19:32,460 --> 00:19:39,700
 I went to work on Easter Tuesday, and when I was leaving work, I was really upset with God.

150
00:19:39,700 --> 00:19:47,240
 And I was, you know, kind of crying out to him as, you know, telling him and asking him, you know, why have you abandoned me?

151
00:19:47,240 --> 00:19:49,280
 I don't understand what you want from me.

152
00:19:49,280 --> 00:19:50,440
 You know, I was upset.

153
00:19:50,440 --> 00:19:57,320
 And when I pulled into the driveway at my house, I turned off the car and I turned on the radio.

154
00:19:57,320 --> 00:20:00,520
 And there God would give me my answer.

155
00:20:00,520 --> 00:20:13,600
 There was, at that exact moment, this elderly gentleman called in the show, and he was talking about all the years that he'd spent praying in front of his local abortion facility, which had been like 30-plus years, you know, of his life.

156
00:20:13,600 --> 00:20:22,380
 And he was just speaking about how important it was, you know, for us to be there and how dedicated he was, you know, to it.

157
00:20:22,380 --> 00:20:28,140
 And the radio host, she replied to him the words that just changed me forever.

158
00:20:28,140 --> 00:20:31,880
 And she said, at the end of our lives, we're all going to stand before God.

159
00:20:31,880 --> 00:20:34,540
 And he's going to ask you, did you know about abortion?

160
00:20:34,540 --> 00:20:41,200
 Did you know that babies were being ripped from their mother's wombs, limb by limb, at the rate of over 3,000 a day?

161
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:47,120
 In the USA, it's 3,000 babies a day, approximately, that die, you know, via abortion.

162
00:20:47,120 --> 00:20:52,040
 And she said, and then he's going to ask you, what did you do?

163
00:20:52,660 --> 00:20:56,680
 And when she said those words, what did you do, I just started to cry.

164
00:20:56,680 --> 00:20:58,960
 I was sobbing uncontrollably.

165
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:09,000
 And I realized, you know, I remember in that moment, I saw myself as a little child standing before God on Judgment Day.

166
00:21:09,720 --> 00:21:14,660
 And I can't, I don't really know why I saw myself as a little girl, right?

167
00:21:14,660 --> 00:21:23,300
 But I saw myself as a little girl standing before God on Judgment and having to try to explain, you know, yes, I knew.

168
00:21:23,740 --> 00:21:26,860
 And God asking, well, what did you do, you know?

169
00:21:26,860 --> 00:21:30,820
 And that's really when it just, it hurt so deeply.

170
00:21:30,820 --> 00:21:34,060
 It was just like a sword piercing my heart.

171
00:21:34,060 --> 00:21:48,740
 And I began to just sob and sob and sob because I was just so filled with grief at realizing in that moment that I had, you know, I had been complicit in helping these mothers take the lives of their babies.

172
00:21:49,920 --> 00:21:56,880
 And that's really that moment where I realized I could never stand by and do nothing again.

173
00:21:56,880 --> 00:22:05,200
 I could not wash my hands of the choices that women were making to take the lives of their babies.

174
00:22:05,200 --> 00:22:09,760
 And that's what I realized is I just will never, ever be silent again.

175
00:22:10,040 --> 00:22:18,360
 And I lacked the courage, you know, to make an effort, you know, at least make the effort to save a life.

176
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:27,580
 And, you know, if it ended up where the woman still chose death, then that was just her choice at that point.

177
